---
Midgaard archives preserve late-era expedition charters and salvage law tablets from the Eastern
Desert. The Granite Arcade holds archival catalog numbers for salt ledger tablets removed from the
desert; some markers reference "shoreward certification" connecting the charter-stone network to the
Saltglass Reach's three cairn lines. Road wardens' use of ritual boundary-sigil repainting derives
from the same Stone Law principle governing Eastern Desert obelisk maintenance: a road with marked
instruments signifies recognized jurisdiction; an unmarked road signifies contested sovereignty.
Eastern Desert conditions are reported through road warden intelligence channels, primarily relevant
for their effect on Roc Road eastern-approach traffic and caravan timing through the desert margin.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy maintains records of desert trade route law descending from the same
Keeper-of-Measure legal tradition. The Neon Covenant's "one ledger, one ration code" echoes the
Salt Ledger Kingdoms' water-debt accounting; founding House Jien employed scribal methods directly
imported from the desert's collapsed ledger courts. House Vao preserved diluted versions of Eastern
Desert water arbitration law, adapted for grain management. The Courier Lantern Office's registry
methodology descends from the same census tradition as the desert's road-charter population counts.
Kowloon's emergency rationing law explicitly cites the desert collapse as the historical case
justifying codified water-shortage protocols.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess Trade Syndics maintain commercial intelligence about eastern desert route conditions relayed
through Midgaard's markets. The Temple of Concord preserves fragments of Keeper-of-Measure survey
prayers repurposed as civic benedictions. Kiess's primary interest is the far end of the east-west
trade logic: desert routes connect through the Saltglass Reach to Mafdet's harbor, reaching Kiess
only after multiple intermediate validations. The Jackal Synod's "authorized thirst" toll courts
represent a direct threat to that chain's continuity. Kiess has no direct charter claims east of the
oasis corridor; the desert's simultaneous legal layers—Keeper obelisk law, Ledger Kingdom water-right
precedent, Synod toll courts, Regent remnant decrees—place it outside Kiess's practical jurisdiction.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's relationship to the Eastern Desert is indirect: desert trade chain disruptions reach Rakuen
as price increases and supply substitutions rather than direct logistical failures. Community memory
of the Eastern Desert is primarily composed of oral traditions from Khenari and Khephari community
members tracing family origin to the desert corridor—these traditions preserve Keeper-period and Salt
Ledger Kingdom accounts that institutional archives do not hold. The Ninth Meridian catastrophe is
preserved in Rakuen's elder oral traditions as a warning about institutional overreach: the attempt
to ritually govern drought cycles by combining astronomical measurement with funerary authority
produced exactly the collapse both systems had been designed to prevent.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses are institutional heirs of the Eastern Desert's administrative tradition:
the Littoral Branch of Measure Script became the foundation of Mafdet's maritime contract notation.
Shoreward Assessors—specialist clerks who translated cargo from inland water-law assessment to
maritime risk-assessment at the Shoreward Seal boundary—are the professional ancestors of current
Ledger House clerks. Mafdet attests desert-origin cargo through the same three-route logic inherited
from the Saltglass Reach: swift-line for high-value goods, heavy-road for bulk commodities,
sealed-route for pyramid-provenance and funerary consignments. The Jackal Synod's Eclipsed Tongues
faction uses Glasswind routes through the Saltglass Reach to move relic materials toward Mafdet's
harbor for maritime export, bypassing inland Synod-controlled inspection—a smuggling pattern Harbor
Wardens track but have not fully suppressed.

flags MIDGAARD KHEPHARI
---
Khephari geological analysis identifies the Iseth Reach drying as the primary structural driver of
collapse: the desert was a managed edge biome between a seasonal river system and a dune interior,
not a pure arid environment. Cistern infrastructure was engineered as overflow governors for flood
conditions, not survival water supply—this tells a Khephari analyst that Keeper-period population
density exceeded what pure arid hydrology could support. Whether the Ninth Meridian Rite accelerated
the drying or merely failed to reverse it is a geological question the thermal event complicated by
overprinting the stratigraphic record in the blast zone. The obelisk system—astronomical calibration
in standing stone—reflects a Keeper understanding that measurement infrastructure must outlast
administrative structures. The obelisks survived when everything else failed because they required
no institutional maintenance to continue casting shadows.

flags MIDGAARD USHABTI
---
Ushabti relationship to the Eastern Desert is jurisdictional and archival: the desert is the original
domain of the administrative systems from which Ushabti legal identity derives. Keepers of Measure,
Salt Ledger Kingdoms, and the Solar Court that commissioned the pyramid complexes all operated
administrative traditions Ushabti trace as ancestral institutional memory. The obelisk system—legal
instruments functioning through shadow-casting rather than armed enforcement—represents the oldest
known instance of the administrative logic Ushabti carry as cultural practice. The Last Sand Regent's
condition—a bound remnant intelligence still issuing decrees to a dead bureaucracy—is, from a Ushabti
perspective, the worst institutional failure mode: administrative authority that has outlasted its
legitimacy source and continues operating through procedural momentum without accountability.

flags MAFDET KHENARI
---
Khenari death-rite geography in the Eastern Desert centers on the pyramid complexes and obelisk
alignments as sacred directional infrastructure. The obelisk shadows marked transitions: the shadow's
edge at specific solar positions was understood by pre-dynastic desert peoples as marking the moment
when the living day shifted toward the territory of the dead. Khenari in Mafdet tracing origin to
eastern desert communities maintain seasonal observances tied to obelisk-shadow timing even without
access to the physical obelisks. The Jackal Tribunal's three sentence classes—Interment, Service,
Correction—map onto Khenari death-rite categories in ways suggesting shared descent from the same
pre-dynastic funerary tradition. The failed Ninth Meridian Rite is preserved in Khenari oral tradition
as the event that separated the living solar law from the dead underworld law: what had been one
administrative system split into two irreconcilable theological factions.
